1🔹 RDD Operations

# Explanation

“In Apache Spark, RDD operations are of two types: transformations, which are lazy and create new RDDs, and actions, which trigger execution and return results.”

# Code

```python
rdd = spark.sparkContext.parallelize([1,2,3,4])

rdd2 = rdd.map(lambda x: x * 2)
print(rdd2.collect())
```

#Why it matters

Lazy evaluation enables optimization before execution.

2🔹 map vs flatMap

#Explanation

“map applies a function to each element and returns one output per input, whereas flatMap can return multiple outputs per input and flattens the result.”

# Code

```python
rdd = spark.sparkContext.parallelize(["hello world"])

print(rdd.map(lambda x: x.split()).collect())
print(rdd.flatMap(lambda x: x.split()).collect())
```

# Why it matters

Used in text processing and flattening nested data.

---

3 🔹 reduceByKey vs groupByKey

# Explanation

“reduceByKey performs aggregation locally before shuffle, making it more efficient, whereas groupByKey shuffles all data first and then aggregates, leading to higher network and memory cost.”

# Code

```python
rdd = spark.sparkContext.parallelize([("a",1),("a",2),("b",1)])

print(rdd.reduceByKey(lambda x,y: x+y).collect())
print(rdd.groupByKey().mapValues(list).collect())
```

# Why it matters

reduceByKey minimizes shuffle → critical for performance.

