## 🔹 zip Operation

### Explanation

“zip combines two RDDs element-wise into pairs, requiring both RDDs to have the same number of partitions and elements.”

### Code

```python
rdd1 = spark.sparkContext.parallelize([1,2,3])
rdd2 = spark.sparkContext.parallelize(["a","b","c"])

print(rdd1.zip(rdd2).collect())
```

### Why it matters

Used for pairing datasets.

---

## 🔹 union Operation

### Explanation

“union combines two RDDs into a single RDD without removing duplicates.”

### Code

```python
rdd1 = spark.sparkContext.parallelize([1,2])
rdd2 = spark.sparkContext.parallelize([2,3])

print(rdd1.union(rdd2).collect())
```

### Why it matters

Useful for merging datasets.

---

## 🔹 distinct Operation

### Explanation

“distinct removes duplicate elements from an RDD by performing a shuffle to ensure uniqueness.”

### Code

```python
rdd = spark.sparkContext.parallelize([1,2,2,3,3])

print(rdd.distinct().collect())
```

### Why it matters

Ensures data uniqueness.

